# Results and Analysis

The optimized CNC machining strategy generated by the AI-based optimization framework was compared with the original machining strategy. The evaluation focused on machining stability, tool wear progression, thermal behavior, and energy consumption.

The optimized strategy uses **6 passes with reduced depth per pass**, while the original machining strategy uses **2 aggressive passes**.

---

## Machining Parameter Comparison

The following figure compares key machining parameters between the original and optimized machining strategies.

- Cutting force
- Surface roughness
- tool wear rate
- vibration amplitude
- cutting temperature
- chip load deviation
- spindle power
- cycle time

Key observations:

• Average cutting force is significantly reduced in the optimized strategy  
• Surface roughness improves due to reduced chip thickness variation  
• Tool wear rate decreases due to lower mechanical load  
• Power consumption is reduced despite increased machining passes  

---

## Tool Wear Progression

Tool wear progression is one of the most important indicators of machining sustainability.

The ISO tool wear limit (VB = 0.07 mm) was used as the failure threshold.

Observations:

• Original strategy reaches the ISO wear limit at approximately **200 pockets**  
• Optimized strategy reaches the same limit at approximately **1000 pockets**  
• This corresponds to nearly **5× improvement in tool life**

The reduction in tool wear is mainly due to:

• lower cutting force  
• reduced cutting temperature  
• improved load distribution across multiple passes

---

## Cutting Temperature Comparison

Cutting temperature directly influences tool wear and machining stability.

Results show:

Original strategy: ~428 °C  
Optimized strategy: ~398 °C  

The reduction in cutting temperature is caused by:

• reduced cutting force per pass  
• smaller chip thickness  
• improved heat distribution during machining

---

## Chip Load Deviation

Chip load deviation measures the stability of chip formation.

Results:

Original strategy: ~3.17  
Optimized strategy: ~2.59  

Lower chip load deviation indicates:

• more uniform material removal  
• reduced chatter risk  
• improved cutting stability

---

## Power Consumption Comparison

Total spindle power consumption was also analyzed.

Results:

Original strategy: ~8200 W  
Optimized strategy: ~7600 W  

Although the optimized strategy uses more passes, the **reduction in instantaneous cutting force lowers overall power demand**.

---

## Spindle Power Trace

The spindle power trace shows how power varies during machining.

Observations:

• Original strategy shows a **large power spike during deep cuts**  
• Optimized strategy distributes power demand more evenly across passes  

This reduces:

• spindle load  
• vibration  
• tool stress

---

## Instantaneous Material Removal Rate (MRR)

Material removal rate comparison shows:

Original strategy:

• very high peak MRR  
• unstable cutting load

Optimized strategy:

• lower peak MRR  
• smoother machining profile

This results in improved machining stability.

---

## Cumulative Machining Depth

The optimized strategy gradually increases cutting depth through multiple passes:

- Pass 1: −3 mm
- Pass 2: −6 mm
- Pass 3: −9 mm
- Pass 4: −12 mm
- Pass 5: −15 mm
- Pass 6: −16 mm

This gradual depth strategy significantly reduces cutting force spikes.

---

## Radar Chart Comparison

The radar chart shows normalized machining parameters for both strategies.

The optimized strategy shows improvements in:

• cutting force  
• surface roughness  
• tool wear  
• vibration  
• power consumption

The only trade-off is **increased cycle time**, which rises from ~16 s to ~36 s.

However, the gains in tool life and machining stability justify this increase.

---

## Toolpath Comparison

The optimized G-code produces a multi-pass circular pocket toolpath.

Original strategy:

• 2 deep cutting passes  

Optimized strategy:

• 6 progressive passes  

This distributes the machining load across multiple tool engagements.

---

# Summary of Improvements

| Metric | Original | Optimized | Improvement |
|------|------|------|------|
Surface Roughness | 20.5 µm | 13.4 µm | 34% improvement |
Cutting Force | 654 | 202 | 69% reduction |
Tool Wear Rate | 2.8×10⁻⁵ | 1.8×10⁻⁵ | 36% reduction |
Vibration | 0.0046 | 0.0033 | 28% reduction |
Temperature | 428°C | 398°C | 7% reduction |
Tool Life | ~200 pockets | ~1000 pockets | 5× improvement |
Cycle Time | 16 s | 36 s | Increased |

---

## Key Insight

The optimization framework successfully improves machining quality and tool life by **redistributing cutting load across multiple passes while maintaining acceptable machining efficiency**.
